    "question_id" : 16546038,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>A &quot;long&quot; greater than the maximum value of long just doesn't exist , rather i suggest you use the biginteger  class , and caste the maximum value of long to a biginteger.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 960307,
      "reputation" : 110397,
      "user_id" : 984823,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/Z2KYN.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Joop Eggen",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/984823/joop-eggen"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1763822428,
    "last_edit_date" : 1763822428,
    "creation_date" : 1763623777,
    "answer_id" : 79825210,
    "question_id" : 16546038,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>This Q&amp;A reappeared after years, but something new.</p>\n<h3>A <code>long</code> as unsigned long</h3>\n<p>There is something though: a <code>long</code> in Java is signed, but interpreting those 64 bits as unsigned long is possible. A <code>String</code> could be parsed with <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Long.html#parseUnsignedLong(java.lang.CharSequence,int,int,int)\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>parseUnsignedLong</code></a>:</p>\n<pre><code>long n = Long.parseUnsignedLong(&quot;...&quot;);\nlong m = Long.MAX_VALUE + 1L;\nlong m = Long.MIN_VALUE + 0L;\n</code></pre>\n<p>You get half of the 64-bit values as extra unsigned long interpretations, so in real world\nprocessing this is an option to consider.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>boolean isBiggerThanMaxLong(long unsignedVal) {\n    return unsignedVal &lt; 0;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<h3>More than a long, <code>BigInteger</code>.</h3>\n<p>Mentioned already.</p>\n"
  } ],
